title: Arbiter event monitor
status: in use
---

# Arbiter event monitor

Live-tail the Arbiter server's `/events` stream (worker done/failed, ReviewGate, inbox) so you don't have to poll.

> [!note] Naming — read this first
> **"The arbiter event monitor" = this live `/events` NDJSON tail.** It is NOT:
> - the internal **`monitor`** runtime component, nor
> - the generic **"Monitor"** operator step (`arb prime` / `arb <id> show`).
> When the docs say "the event monitor," they mean the loop below.

Route is `/events` (NOT `/api/events`, which 404s). Served as `application/x-ndjson` from `<%= @host %>`.

> [!todo] Run the monitor — self-healing loop (re-mints a fresh token each cycle, streams directly)
> ```bash
> while true; do
>   TOKEN=$(arb mcp token mint --tier coordinator --json 2>/dev/null | jq -r .token)
>   /usr/bin/curl -sN --connect-timeout 8 --max-time 240 \
>     "<%= @host %>/events?token=$TOKEN&subscribe=worker_done,worker_failed,review_gate,inbox" \
>     2>/dev/null \
>   | /usr/bin/grep --line-buffered -aE '"at"'
>   sleep 1
> done
> ```
> Each cycle re-mints a fresh token then streams. Survives token expiry and stream drops.

> [!info]- Why each flag
> - **`--max-time 240`** — recycle the connection every 4 min so a network blip drops one cycle instead of hanging forever.
> - **`--connect-timeout 8`** — fail fast if the server's unreachable; the `while` + `sleep 1` reconnects.
> - **`grep -aE '"at"'`** — every real event carries an `"at"` timestamp; this filters out SSE keepalives. `--line-buffered` surfaces events immediately.
> - **absolute `/usr/bin/curl` & `/usr/bin/grep`** — on macOS zsh/mise the `command_not_found_handler` can choke on bare commands inside a loop.
> - **`subscribe=…`** — the event classes worth waking for; adjust to taste.

> [!warning] Don't tunnel the long-lived stream
> If the server is remote, connect to it directly — do NOT wrap the long-lived stream in `ssh` (or any transport that can wedge half-open). A blip then makes the monitor go silently deaf — no error, it just stops receiving, and `curl --max-time` can't kill a wedged tunnel. A one-shot token mint over `ssh` is fine; the stream must be direct.

## Running it inside an agent

**Claude Code:** run the loop via the **Monitor tool** with `persistent: true`, so each event line becomes a chat notification. Do NOT use a `run_in_background` Bash — an infinite loop never exits, so it never notifies; it only buffers to a file.

**Other agents (Codex, Antigravity, etc.):** use your harness's own persistent-background / output-streaming primitive if it has one; otherwise run the loop as a background process and poll its output, or skip live-tailing and rely on the mailbox.

> [!danger] Backstop — the stream is not durable
> There's no replay across the ~1s reconnect gap, so an event landing exactly then won't print. **`arb message inbox` is the source of truth**; the stream is only for live watching.
